    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>Detecting cold dust in a pulsar planet system</prj:name>
        <prj:note>With the requested continuum sensitivity of 0.01 mJy/beam, we will probe down to 4.7 Earth masses of cold (15 K) dust around the pulsar PSR B1257+12, which hosts multiple terrestrial planets. The detection of such a reservoir of dust would indicate the presence of a populous planetesimal belt at large orbital radii, consistent with the model prediction that compact systems of multiple terrestrial planets are correlated with debris disks. A non-detection would constrain the planetesimal formation process in massive, dusty fallback disks around neutron stars, as it would imply that these systems do not produce hidden planetesimal reservoirs that are substantially larger than those around main sequence stars.</prj:note>
