    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Some pulsars are known to host planets of up to a few Earth masses. The origin of these planets is still unknown, but they may have coagulated out of a circumstellar disk of residual material related to the supernova. Such fallback disks of dust have been found around young  neutron stars. If the planets formed in such a disk, a remnant planetesimal disk may still be producing observable amounts of dusty debris. We propose to put the most stringent limits to date on the amount of cold dust around a planet-hosting pulsar. If a dusty disk is found, it will provide strong constraints for the planetesimal and planet formation process in disks around neutron stars and may reveal new insight 
into terrestrial planet formation.</prp:abstract>
